mQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.l22FCLmGalu4Xs4GzQ0OhY8TOr8cRLLmLvkD8GMmtCScX=
fun9FnBCzOo5Tz_lZmk1A_6FqPBvEODe6LuNKS6j_WD4u8XcWFu4G9dibQV78cq-sw_zR_NVSmT=
M8IHWVV-1oA6Cf_TvEXpKkqusYABtYT_DJCIeqbdIBBLoAytZeAhQS343ysfWZ9T8YJGYuSSrPH=
JBVIsitBH-5ZNsMfYlpapEoi93xqLduXbh6wt8UTL5b8FOoqjikj06s63dDebfRdk2lcMqVvQWz=
bgseqa_Qf9MLOwiRXmMMIBxMkKVdgqSEXkH2BRimvz2h8bemFbQkSNMcFQ-2CfqUADgp-OVQ ) =
, and I thought it=E2=80=99d be interesting to do a two-month on retrospect=
ive of the device generally. But before we get to that, you=E2=80=99ve had =
a very interesting and long career in tech and I=E2=80=99d love to learn mo=
re about you. Where are you from originally? How did you get started in tec=
h? What was the path from childhood on?*

*HB:* I was born and raised in Brazil and was gifted the book Being Digital=
 ( https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/120521/being-digital-by-nichola=
s-negroponte/ ) by Nicholas Negroponte ( https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nich=
olas_Negroponte ) when I was starting to think about college. I became pret=
ty obsessed with the idea of going to school at MIT. My mother is an archit=
ect, my father is an engineer, the Media Lab at MIT ( https://www.media.mit=
.edu/ ) is part of the architecture department in a very funky way or conne=
cted to it I should say, and it was just the right thing. So I got into tec=
h through the history of the Media Lab and then finally making my way to MI=
T in 1996. I spent my entire time, both in college and after college, for t=
wenty years working in mobile, back in the Palm Pilot days through the Pock=
et PC era and beyond, and crossed paths with you about halfway through I th=
ink that mobile career.

*So tell me about Lobby7, this was a voice oriented startup you started aft=
er college, right? I know it was acquired by Nuance Communication, which wa=
s well-known for their Dragon NaturallySpeaking dictation technology. I thi=
nk Apple licensed that for Siri, then Microsoft acquired Nuance outright, b=
ut it feels like one of those technologies in the long run where, of course=
, the big companies own it, but what drew you to voice as a medium even way=
 back in the early days?*

*HB:* I was pretty heavily influenced by my thesis advisor at MIT, Dr. Patt=
ie Maes ( https://www.media.mit.edu/people/pattie/overview/ ) from the Medi=
a Lab. Lobby7, which by the way was a temporary name we gave the company. I=
t=E2=80=99s the lobby to building seven, which is the main entrance to MIT,=
 and it was totally one of those temporary names that just stayed.

*It=E2=80=99s a good name, I like it.*

*HB:* We had a choice between mobile gaming and mobile speech recognition. =
I still don=E2=80=99t quite recall why the heck we picked mobile speech rec=
ognition instead of a very profitable mobile gaming trajectory, but we did,=
 and the company didn=E2=80=99t last very long. We ran out of money after a=
bout three years, got acquired by Nuance, but were given a budget in severa=
l years of time to develop what we thought was the next or a big part of th=
e next major UI paradigm as mobile came into focus, which was speech recogn=
ition. So what we built at Nuance eventually became, I was long gone by the=
 time it launched, but eventually became the cloud backend to Apple=E2=80=
=99s first version of Siri, their voice assistant. But I was long gone, I j=
oined Google in 2008.

*We=E2=80=99ll get to Google, but I think this is going to be a pattern we=
=E2=80=99re going to throughout your career, where you=E2=80=99ve latched o=
nto paradigms that make sense to be the thing but maybe a few years early. =
And I=E2=80=99m just curious, what has drawn you to that as far as you=E2=
=80=99re starting with voice? We=E2=80=99ll get to the VR stuff in a little=
 bit, but it does seem to be a bit of a pattern.*

*HB:* Yeah, it=E2=80=99s interesting, and I probably don=E2=80=99t think ab=
out it nearly as much as I should, because I could probably learn a few les=
sons from my own story there. Mobile to me was an obvious thing, it was obv=
ious that the world was going to go through this computing paradigm shift. =
It was a matter of when, not a matter of if, and I had access to a lot of p=
eople who were early thinkers in the space, a lot of interesting research t=
hat came out of MIT and I just felt like the UI part of the problem was one=
 that no one had really started to attack yet. When we=E2=80=99re looking f=
or an idea to focus an entire company in your career for many years, you lo=
ok for those kinds of problems. So I don=E2=80=99t think we were deeply tho=
ughtful about why speech mattered, it just felt like some of the early rese=
arch was pointing in an interesting direction and you definitely needed to =
rethink the way speech was done.

We ended up contributing to an IEEE standard for distributed speech recogni=
tion very early on in the life of the company but it was really accidental,=
 I think, that we ended up where we did in choosing speech. And you=E2=80=
=99re right, it took quite a bit longer than I think any of us expected, I =
think it wouldn=E2=80=99t be unfair to say that speech is still fighting it=
s way into the mobile computing paradigm.

*Is it one of those things where =E2=80=94 you mentioned that Nuance was th=
e cloud backend for Siri =E2=80=94 but eventually it just has to be local a=
nd almost the biggest constraint was having local devices that were power e=
nough and capable enough to have the immediacy and the interaction and expe=
rience that=E2=80=99s going to be key for taking off?*

*HB:* Early on, you knew that you couldn=E2=80=99t run it locally because y=
ou needed an extremely powerful compute-hungry system to handle the large d=
ictionaries and grammars that we needed for those types of tasks like searc=
hing a large database or speaking using a somewhat natural UI. So we knew t=
hat we couldn=E2=80=99t put those things on the device=E2=80=99s client sid=
e at all, and we had very, very little bandwidth available. We=E2=80=99re t=
alking back in the CDPD days, pre-GPRS where you had 12 kilobits per second=
 of bandwidth available to you with relatively high latency.

So the first challenge that we tackled was, =E2=80=9CHow can we do some amo=
unt of the operations of speech recognition client side that was not comput=
e-intensive, but that would strip down the signal enough that you could str=
eam it in relatively real-time fashion to the server and then recognized?=
=E2=80=9D. The first DSR standard that we helped create at IEE had us down =
to about five or six kilobits per second without any loss in the quality of=
 the signal. We were doing feature extraction, essentially creating vectors=
 out of the signal client site and then shipping those to a server that kne=
w how to put it back together and a lot of how speech is done is still toda=
y, but the blocks have moved back to the client side, thankfully, so we can=
 do things faster.

*It=E2=80=99s amazing how much of tech innovation and development is really=
 about fancier and fancier compression capabilities.*

*HB:* Completely, from the very beginning.

Android
-------

*So from there, from Nuance, you go to Google. I think you were working on =
some voice stuff there early, then you switch over to Android. I think this=
 is where people in our audience, who know who you are, probably comes from=
 that era. You were very much the face of Android. It was a very fun era, G=
oogle and Apple going back and forth, some very spicy Google I/Os that you =
were associated with. As you look back a decade on, what stands out to you =
about that era?*

*HB:* It was probably the most fascinating thing that I=E2=80=99ve ever bee=
n part of, because the arrival of iOS and the iPhone created existential ri=
sk for an entire ecosystem of OEMs, Samsung and HTC, and at the time, we st=
ill had LG and Sony and so many other names in the space, and Android was t=
he right antidote at the right time with the backing and the desire to re-a=
rm that ecosystem with the operating system that it needed to stand up and =
compete against the giant that clearly was coming our way.

It was equal parts developer excitement, user excitement. We had such a hug=
e base of hardcore tech fans who loved Android and wanted to be part of it =
and the other third of it was obviously the OEM ecosystem and just how exci=
ted they were to be the next phone selected to be the first vessel for the =
next version of Android and so on. So it was really 360-degree excitement, =
and we just had to keep our heads down and make sure that we were moving as=
 fast as possible.

*Yeah, that=E2=80=99s definitely the one example =E2=80=94 you weren=E2=80=
=99t ahead of the wave, you were directly on top of the wave and you=E2=80=
=99re going to go where it might take you.*

*HB:* Yeah, and it was just really fun to have such a formidable competitor=
